The severity of a crime in accordance with the legislation is determined by the maximum punishment provided for in the sanction of the article. According to the Criminal Code of the Kyrgyz Republic, crimes are classified based on their character and degree of public danger into four categories: 

1) Minor crimes - intentional and negligent crimes for which imprisonment is not provided; 
2) Less serious crimes - intentional crimes punishable by imprisonment for no more than five years, and negligent crimes punishable by imprisonment for no more than ten years; 
3) Serious crimes - intentional crimes punishable by imprisonment for more than five years but not exceeding ten years; 
4) Especially serious crimes - intentional crimes punishable by imprisonment for more than ten years or life imprisonment. 

This classification is outlined in Article 19 of the Criminal Code of the Kyrgyz Republic.

The specific information that must be included in the written application for recognition and enforcement of a foreign court's decision, as outlined in the Civil Procedure Code of the Kyrgyz Republic, Article 430, includes:

1. The name of the court to which the application is submitted;
2. The name and location of the foreign court;
3. The name of the applicant (creditor), their representative (if applicable), and their place of residence or location;
4. The name of the debtor, along with their place of residence or location or the location of the debtor's property;
5. The applicant's request for recognition and enforcement of the foreign court's decision or a specification of when enforcement is required;
6. A list of attached documents.

Additionally, it may include contact details (such as phone numbers, faxes, email addresses) for the applicant, debtor, and their representatives if necessary for proper and timely consideration of the case.

Yes, there are exceptions to the requirement for the return of unjust enrichment as mentioned in the Civil Code of the Kyrgyz Republic. Article 1030 states that unless otherwise provided by this Code, other laws, or the nature of the relevant relationships, the rules outlined in this chapter also apply to claims for the return of the following: 
1) performed under a void transaction; 
2) recovery of property from illegal possession by another owner; 
3) obligations related to return executed based on such obligations; 
4) damage compensation, including harm caused by the dishonest behavior of the enriched party.

The details that must be included in a contract for the establishment of a voluntary servitude are:

1) A description of the land burdened by the servitude and the land for which the servitude is established;
2) The terms and duration of the servitude;
3) A plan or map of the land indicating the location of the servitude.

This is based on Article 54 of the Land Code of the Kyrgyz Republic.

The severity of a crime is defined by the maximum penalty provided for in the sanction of the article, as stated in Article 19 of the Criminal Code of the Kyrgyz Republic. Crimes are classified into four categories: 

1) Minor crimes are those for which imprisonment is not provided; 
2) Less serious crimes are punishable by up to five years of imprisonment; 
3) Serious crimes are punishable by more than five years but no more than ten years of imprisonment; 
4) Particularly serious crimes are punishable by over ten years of imprisonment or life imprisonment.

The written application for the recognition and enforcement of a foreign court decision must include the following specific information as per Article 430 of the Civil Procedure Code of the Kyrgyz Republic:

1) The name of the court where the application is submitted;
2) The name and location of the foreign court;
3) The name of the claimant and their representative (if applicable), along with their residential or business address;
4) The name of the debtor, their residential or business address, or the location of the debtor's assets;
5) The claimant's request for the recognition and enforcement of the foreign court decision or the indication of when enforcement is required;
6) A list of attached documents.

Additionally, it may include contact information such as phone numbers, fax numbers, and email addresses of the claimant, the debtor, and their representatives if necessary for the proper and timely consideration of the case.

The conditions allowing a taxpayer to petition for a deferral or installment payment of tax debt are stated in Article 91 of the Tax Code of the Kyrgyz Republic. A taxpayer may apply for deferral or installment in relation to tax debts that are not being settled for the following reasons:

1) Damage caused to the taxpayer due to circumstances of force majeure;
2) Delay in financing or payment from the budget for goods supplied, work performed, and services rendered by this taxpayer, as well as within the framework of activities in accordance with the legislation of the Kyrgyz Republic on public-private partnerships;
3) If the financial or property situation of the taxpayer excludes the possibility of one-time payment of the tax debt.

Deferral or installment can vary from one month to three years.
